def: The place in which public records or historic documents arekept.Our words . . . . become records in God's court, and are laid up inhis archives as witnesses. Gov. of Tongue.
The bones of the cranium; more especially, the bones of thedomelike upper portion.
Open or spongy, as some porous bones.
Mutually visible, or in sight, the one from the other, asstations.
A fabric resembling velvet, but having the nap flat and lessclose.
In a improvident manner. "Improvidently rash." Drayton.
To become squeamish; to feel nausea; to turn away with disgust.
To decide to be heresy or a heretic; to denounce as a hereticor heretical. Bp. Hall.And let no one be minded, on the score of my neoterism, to hereticateme. Fitzed. Hall.
